                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72119/7737: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Commission to Negotiate Peace</gloss>
                        to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-11-12T10:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 12, 1919—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 12:36 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5137. From Polk for the Secretary of State. I understand from telegrams that
                    treaty may possibly be rejected. What position do you desire Peace Mission to
                    take here in that event? If the treaty is defeated and the decision is final, it
                    would seem possible for someone to raise a question in regard to our continuing
                    to sit in the preparation of other treaties along the lines of the treaty with
                    Germany. Should Commission withdraw or continue to participate in discussions of
                    Bulgarian and other treaty questions? In the latter <pb facs="0699" n="661"
                        xml:id="pg_661"/> case, the position of the Commission might seem to be
                    inconsistent. I would appreciate receiving your views at the earliest moment
                    possible. Polk.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Mission</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
